## 🤝 Promises

A Promise is an object representing the **eventual success or failure** of an async operation. It has 3 states: **pending**, **fulfilled**, **rejected**.

### Creating a Promise
```js
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  const success = true;

  if (success) {
    resolve("Data loaded!");   // fulfilled
  } else {
    reject("Error occurred!"); // rejected
  }
});
```

### Consuming a Promise
```js
promise
  .then(result => {
    console.log(result);   // "Data loaded!"
    return result.toUpperCase();  // chain it
  })
  .then(upper => console.log(upper))  // "DATA LOADED!"
  .catch(error => console.error(error))   // handles rejection
  .finally(() => console.log("Done"));    // always runs
```

### Promise Chaining
```js
fetchUser(1)
  .then(user => fetchPosts(user.id))
  .then(posts => fetchComments(posts[0].id))
  .then(comments => console.log(comments))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
// Much cleaner than callback hell!
```

### Promise Utilities
```js
// All must succeed — fails fast if any rejects
Promise.all([p1, p2, p3])
  .then(([result1, result2, result3]) => { ... });

// Wait for ALL, success or failure
Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3])
  .then(results => results.forEach(r => console.log(r.status)));

// First to settle (resolve OR reject)
Promise.race([p1, p2, p3]).then(first => { ... });

// First to RESOLVE (ignores rejections)
Promise.any([p1, p2, p3]).then(first => { ... });

// Immediately resolved/rejected
Promise.resolve("value")
Promise.reject(new Error("fail"))
```

